# Java Standards

- Prefer interfaces for external dependencies (HTTP clients, DB, queues). Inject via constructor or builder.
- Keep methods small and single-purpose; extract private methods when logic grows.
- Use parameterized tests (JUnit 5 `@ParameterizedTest`) for multiple inputs; one test method per behavior.
- No comments for obvious logic; short comments only for non-obvious or spec-critical behavior.
- Preserve existing patterns in the codebase when adding code.
- Prefer immutable DTOs (records, or final fields + constructor).

## Parameterized test shape (JUnit 5)

```java
@ParameterizedTest
@CsvSource({"input1,expected1", "input2,expected2"})
void parsePrefs(String input, String expected) {
    var got = Parser.parsePrefs(input);
    assertThat(got).isEqualTo(expected);
}

// Or @MethodSource for complex cases
@ParameterizedTest
@MethodSource("parsePrefsCases")
void parsePrefs(String input, Preference want, boolean wantErr) {
    if (wantErr) {
        assertThrows(InvalidInputException.class, () -> Parser.parsePrefs(input));
    } else {
        assertThat(Parser.parsePrefs(input)).isEqualTo(want);
    }
}
```

## Error handling

- Use exceptions; do not swallow. Wrap with cause: `throw new MyException("context", e)`.
- For retries/backoff, use explicit intervals (e.g. from spec: 1 min, 5 min, 15 min).
